'''Mladen <U+0160>ubari<U+0107>''' (born 1920) is a Croatian [[chess]] master.

In 1939 he tied for 3rd-4th in Zagreb ([[Svetozar Gligori<U+0107>]] won).<ref name="Vjesnik">{{cite web | url=http://www.vjesnik.com/pdf/2001%5C03%5C25%5C31A31.PDF | title=Kronologija hrvatskog <U+0161>aha (356): Kolo iznena<U+0111>enja | date=March 25, 2001 | work=[[Vjesnik]] | language=Croatian | format=PDF | accessdate=2009-05-10}}</ref>  In December 1941, he played at fourth board against dr Pazman (2 : 0) in a match Croatia <U+2013> Slovakia in Zagreb.<ref name="Vjesnik"/> <U+0160>ubari<U+0107> took 9th at Munich 1942 ([[European Individual Chess Championship]], ''Wertungsturnier'' <U+2013> Qualification Tournament, [[G<U+00F6>sta Danielsson]] won).<ref>[http://www.rogerpaige.me.uk/tables13.htm 1942<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>Gillam, Anthony J. & Swift, A J (2001), 1st European championship Munich 1942, Nottingham: The Chess Player, ISBN 1-901034-46-1</ref>

After [[World War II]], he played several times in [[Yugoslav Chess Championship]]. In 1945 he tied for 12-16th in Novi Sad ([[Petar Trifunovi<U+0107>]] won).<ref name="Vjesnik"/>
In 1946 he tied for 14-16th in Zagreb (Trifunovi<U+0107> won).<ref>[http://www.rogerpaige.me.uk/Tables%2017.htm 1946<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 1948, he tied for 17-18th in Belgrade (Gligori<U+0107> and [[Vasja Pirc]] won).<ref>[http://www.rogerpaige.me.uk/Tables%2019.htm 1948<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

In other tournaments, he won ahead of [[Mijo Udov<U+010D>i<U+0107>]] at Zagreb 1948,<ref name="Vjesnik"/> and took 2nd, behind [[Braslav Rabar]], at Zagreb 1950 (CRO-ch).

